{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dcb9e249-273b-47e0-8f1e-be0e719b3c00","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the system automatically generates a **crash report**. Look here:\n\n1. **User-level reports:**\n   `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n2. **System-level reports:**\n   `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS versions). Open them with any text editor — they contain the stack trace, exception type, and register state.\n\n**To get a core dump** instead, run before launching your app:\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\n\nCore files typically land in `/cores/core.<pid>`. You can then inspect with `lldb`:\n\n```bash\nlldb --core /cores/core.12345 ./YourApp\n```\n\n> **Tip:** Use `Console.app` → *Crash Reports* for a GUI view of all reports.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c7b5165e-a000-4094-96ed-f96f99301ade","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":291},"id":"5df22c86-af21-4be5-a4c6-68eab8f386b5","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:58:26.835Z","parentId":"cf2c5be6-f510-446f-a15c-5a8bdc238596"}
